templateAssets.content:
The Biophysics major is designed to provide students with a flexible scientific/technical training that allows them to explore different career paths and tailor their class work to their scientific interests. The program aims at providing an opportunity to the students to become scientific leaders, bringing the analytic and experimental techniques of different fields to bear on the fascinating world of the physics of living systems.


Listed below are the lower division preparation courses for the major.


To be considered for admission to this major, you must complete the following courses by the end of spring before transfer:

  • One and a half years of Calculus through Multivariable,
  • One course in Linear Algebra,
  • One year of Calculus Based Physics (Mechanics, Electricity, and Magnetism),

It is STRONGLY RECOMMENDED that the remainder of the major prep be completed prior to transfer: One course in Differential Equations, One year of General Chemistry, One course in Biology with Lab for the major (Cellular, Molecular), and Additional calculus-based physics courses.


All courses must be taken for a letter grade.


For more information regarding this major and UCLA's transfer selection process, visit https://www.pa.ucla.edu and https://admission.ucla.edu.


PLEASE NOTE: the community college courses listed below have been approved to satisfy the preparation requirements for this major at UCLA, but they may not be exact equivalents of the UCLA courses listed.

The AP Exam Scores listed below may be used to satisfy the major prep:

  • A score of 4 or higher on the AP Physics C Mechanics exam may be used in place of Physics 1A.
  • A score of 4 or higher on the AP Chemistry exam may be used in place of Chem 20A.  
  • A score of 5 on AP Calculus AB exam is equivalent to Math 31A and can be used in place of this calculus course.
  • A score of 5 on the AP Calculus BC exam is equivalent to Math 31A and 31B and can be used in place of these calculus courses. 


The IB Exam Scores listed below may be used to satisfy the major prep:

  • A score of 6 or higher on the IB HL Analysis & Approaches exam is equivalent to Math 31A and can be used in place of this calculus course.
